header: YouGov / Mayor of London Survey Results
content: Are you satisfied or dissatisfied with the job that Sadiq Khan is doing as Mayor of London?
How sure or unsure are you about your opinion of how Sadiq Khan is doing as Mayor of London?

To keep up with demand, [LONDON BOROUGH] will need to build around 2,000 homes each year. To achieve this they might need to enact some but not all of the following policies.  
Given that, to what extent do you support or oppose the following in [LONDON BOROUGH]?
Increasing the density of new developments (e.g. by making new buildings higher or closer together)
Building more on brownfield land, including developments that mix homes and workplaces
Creating more homes in existing residential areas close to train stations and town centres
Requiring developers to include more genuinely affordable homes in their developments
Increasing the number of part-buy/part-rent homes
Ensuring that when public land is sold off it includes a high proportion of affordable housing
Increasing the number of low-rent homes for Londoners on low incomes
Improving standards in the private rented sector (e.g. by promoting more secure tenancies)
Ensuring that all new homes worth up to £350,000 are available to Londoners first, ahead of overseas buyers

Experts say that around 60,000 homes need to be built across London each year to tackle the housing crisis. To achieve this they might need to enact some but not all of the following policies.
Given that, to what extent do you support or oppose the following activities in London?
Increasing the density of new developments (e.g. by making new buildings higher or closer together)
Building more on brownfield land, including developments that mix homes and workplaces
Creating more homes in existing residential areas close to train stations and town centres
Requiring developers to include more genuinely affordable homes in their developments
Increasing the number of part-buy/part-rent homes
Ensuring that when public land is sold off it includes a high proportion of affordable housing
Increasing the number of low-rent homes for Londoners on low incomes
Improving standards in the private rented sector (e.g. by promoting more secure tenancies)
Ensuring that all new homes worth up to £350,000 are available to Londoners first, ahead of overseas buyers
Which two or three, if any, of the following proposals would you MOST like to see the Mayor of London deliver? (Please select up to three)
Ensuring that all new homes worth up to £350,000 are available to Londoners first, ahead of overseas buyers
Increasing the number of low-rent homes for Londoners on low incomes
Requiring developers to include more genuinely affordable homes in their developments
Ensuring that when public land is sold off it includes a higher proportion of affordable housing
Improving standards in the private rented sector (e.g. promoting more secure tenancies)
Doubling housebuilding to at least 60,000 new homes a year
Building more on brownfield land, including developments that mix homes and workplaces
Increasing the number of part-buy/part-rent homes
Creating more homes in existing residential areas close to train stations and town centres
Increasing the density of new developments (e.g. by making new buildings higher or closer together)
What do you think are the two or three biggest problems with renting privately in London? (Please select up to three)
The condition and quality of the property (e.g. too damp, dark, draughty)
The up-front cost of tenancy deposits
Short-term contracts meaning renters don’t know how long they will be able to stay in their property
Renters feeling that they have little power to improve their situation due to fear of eviction
The safety standards of the property
The process of getting deposits back
Which two or three of the following do you think the Mayor should do next to improve private renting in London? (Please rank your top three)
Support councils to crack down on criminal landlords and agents locally
Persuade the Government to introduce landlord licensing and registration schemes
Call on the Government to review the financial support available for low and middle income renters
Launch an online database of criminal landlords and agents
Set up an independent London commission to decide how the rental sector should be reformed
Persuade businesses to offer their employees support with the cost of renting, for instance by offering tenancy deposit loans schemes
How willing, if at all, would you be to use the following to help you monitor air pollution?
Use your smart phone to monitor air pollution
Carry an air pollution monitor about the size of a mobile phone when walking
Carry an air pollution monitor about the size of a mobile phone when cycling
Attach an air pollution monitor about the size of a mobile phone to your car
Install an air quality monitor about the size of a mobile phone in your home
Which of the following would most convince you to carry or use an air pollution monitor, or do you find neither of these arguments convincing?
If I knew it would help monitor and map air pollution across London
If I knew it would help measure my personal air pollution exposure
Neither of these would convince me to carry or use an air pollution monitor
To what extent, if at all, would you say air pollution is a problem...?

On 23rd October 2017 the Mayor of London will introduce a Toxicity Charge on the oldest, most polluting vehicles travelling in the centre of London.
Which of the following, if any, would best convince you that the Toxicity Charge is good for London? (Please rank your top three)
Air pollution damages children’s lungs, with children in inner London having around 10 per cent less lung capacity than normal for this age
Air pollution causes 40,000 premature death a year in the UK, including over 9,000 in London,
As part of the scheme, small businesses and poorer residents will be able to scrap affected vehicles through a government funded vehicle scrappage fund
This is the just first step towards expanding the Ultra-Low Emission Zone up to the North/South Circular for all vehicles by 2021
Residents within the toxicity charge area will benefit from a discount to the charge
Only 8% vehicles will actually pay the charge
